metadata.name: In Due Time #49
metadata.description:
“In Due Time” is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht’s mastery of line and Vittoria’s notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria’s poem for the collection:

“In Due Time”
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

To save a high-resolution image for printing, click “open” under the image on the page for your token, and then hit:

Digits “1” through “9” to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #3
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Helios #27
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Helios' attempts to capture something of the nature of light; in particular, its fleeting nature and its ability to bring color and joy.

Containing basic minimalist forms, each 'Helios' output forms a bold, evocative design.

To download:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: COMPACT #1
Puzzles & Mysteries #89
metadata.description:
Nothing is true to reality about this piece.
Not the sky, nor the hills and definitely not the colors. 
It’s all about getting lost in a place we don’t know - A puzzle, a mystery and collecting the missing pieces.

Press “s” to save as png.

Made with p5js;

metadata.name: Blobby #79
metadata.description:
A sphere that has been contorted (or not) in various fashions! 

The spike level indicates how dense the protrusions are and the displacement level indicates how far these protrusions go. If any of those are 0, you'll get a flat sphere.

metadata.name: Intertwine #79
metadata.description:
An exploration of a distorted grid with twisted lines and connected colorpoints. Creating a wide range of abstract and organic compositions.

Press s in live mode for a 2000x2800 download

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje January 2023

metadata.name: Tangentum #235
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Pine Dream #50
metadata.description:
Pine dream by Asaf Slook (2022)

This work is an attempt to create a simple pen-like generated drawing, in a way that confuses the observer to perceive it to be a real unique hand-drawn piece.

Rare features:
- Lonely tree
- Static stroke
- Sunny day palette
- Dotted land
- Partial land
 
The best results are from 1000x1000 and above.

This work was created using p5.js and love :)

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #235
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

metadata.name: spinlock punchcard #38
metadata.description:
we say nothing, letting them collect and pile.

then complicate the lock. hoard. arrange. and again.

logic becomes soft, alluring; hiding truths or attempts to decipher.

instead, showcasing card houses as architectural virtuosity.

[ in “live view” you can press: ]
[ S or 1 : save 3000x3000 png ]
[ 2 :  save 6000x6000 png ]
[ 3 :  save 12000x12000 png ]

metadata.name: Tempus Fugit #15
metadata.description:
This collection combines several classical techniques (Isometric 3D, voxels, noise fields, and unusual Truchet tilings) into something new.

In some pieces, the base 3d structure dissolves, creating an abstract, twisted painting
with only an elusive sense of the underlying construction logic.

Others are more architectural. Are they decaying cities from another age ? Deteriorating landscapes for the Minecraft generation ? Strange artifacts from a long gone alien civilization ? The viewer will decide.

All iterations, though, are designed to express this common feeling that time erodes everything. Tempus Fugit.


Made with p5.js only (no webgl).

Key commands:
's' - save to png
'1', '2, '4' - change resolution

metadata.name: SYSTEM_HASH #13
metadata.description:
generative universes containing arbitrary matter with arbitrary properties // emergent physics unique to each piece

note: because this is a physics simulation the screen coordinates are important with regard to the plane the objects exist on and so the script is deterministic _as long as you use the same window dimensions_, this also means you can play around with different sizes.
